misconceptions.inferred_category_name: Mismatch between spec output and always-printing a 'Found' message
misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes printing "Found at index:" is always appropriate, even when the value isn’t found (i.e., when the index is -1). They may think the presence of -1 automatically communicates "not found" to the user without needing different wording.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: In Java, the computer only prints exactly what you program. While using -1 as a sentinel is correct, the *message* still says "Found" even when not found. The program does not infer intent from the value -1; you must explicitly choose output text/format that matches the specification (e.g., print -1 or change the message when not found).
misconceptions.error_manifestation: Wrong output / specification mismatch (prints a misleading message like "Found at index: -1").
